#let images = (
  "7.1": (
    caption: [Natural selection favors large and small gametes over medium-sized gametes. Initially, there are three gamete sizes. Natural selection acts against medium-sized gametes because they are not as mobile as small gametes and do not provide as many resources as large gametes. Over time, only small gametes (sperm) and large gametes (eggs) persist.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-28-22-10-23.png"
  ),
  "7.2": (
    caption: [Competition for mates can be direct and physical. (A) Male deer use their antlers in battles for access to females. (B) Male horses also engage in physical competition for mating opportunities.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-28-22-10-49.png"
  ),
  "7.3": (
    caption: [In the direct benefits model of female mate choice, females select mates who provide tangible resources that increase their fitness. This graph shows that female fitness is maximized when they choose males providing an optimal size of nuptial gift, leading natural selection to favor a female preference for that specific male trait.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-28-22-11-19.png"
  ),
  "7.4": (
    caption: [A male scorpionfly (top) presents a nuptial gift, a blowfly, to a female (bottom). The female consumes the prey item during copulation, receiving a direct nutritional benefit.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-28-22-11-29.png"
  ),
  "7.5": (
    caption: [Nuptial gift size directly influences mating duration and success in scorpionflies. (A) Copulation duration increases with the size of the nuptial prey, plateauing for gifts larger than 19 mm². (B) Longer copulation times result in a greater number of sperm being transferred to the female.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-28-22-11-43.png"
  ),
  "7.6": (
    caption: [Female pronghorns appear to select males based on good genes, as indicated by harem-holding ability. Offspring of males with large harems (attractive males) show significantly higher survival rates over time compared to offspring from other males, suggesting that females' choices confer genetic benefits to their young.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-28-22-12-13.png"
  ),
  "7.7": (
    caption: [The peacock's tail is a classic example of an elaborate and costly secondary sexual trait. Its size and ornamentation are believed to have evolved through female choice, signaling the male's genetic quality.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-28-22-12-25.png"
  ),
  "7.8": (
    caption: [Sexual selection often leads to striking differences in coloration between sexes. The male red-knobbed hornbill displays much more vibrant and elaborate coloration than the female, a trait favored by female mate choice.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-28-22-12-33.png"
  ),
  "7.9": (
    caption: [Female sticklebacks may use male coloration as an indicator of parasite resistance. The vibrant red color of males is a signal of health and good genes, making them more attractive mates.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-28-22-12-55.png"
  ),
  "7.10": (
    caption: [Female sticklebacks show a clear preference for more brightly colored males. (A) More colorful (redder) males are in better health (higher condition factor). (B) Females spend more time with brighter males. (C) When the red color is filtered out, the preference for these males disappears, confirming that color is the key cue.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-28-22-13-27.png"
  ),
  "7.11": (
    caption: [Female sticklebacks prefer males with a greater number of MHC (Major Histocompatibility Complex) alleles. Females spent more time near males with a higher diversity of MHC alleles, suggesting they choose mates that can provide offspring with stronger immune systems.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-28-22-13-42.png"
  ),
  "7.12": (
    caption: [Female sticklebacks use chemical cues (peptides) to assess male MHC quality. When the combined number of MHC alleles between a pair was suboptimal, females were attracted to water supplemented with synthetic MHC peptides. Conversely, when the pair's combined alleles were optimal, supplemented water was less attractive.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-28-22-14-04.png"
  ),
  "7.13": (
    caption: [Male stalk-eyed flies exhibit variation in the length of their eye stalks, a trait under sexual selection. Experiments involving artificial selection for long and short eye stalks have been used to test the runaway selection model.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-28-22-14-16.png"
  ),
  "7.14": (
    caption: [The sensory exploitation model proposes that female preference (P+) for a male trait (T) can evolve before the male trait itself appears. In this phylogeny, the preference is ancestral, and once the trait (T+) appears in a lineage, it is immediately favored by females.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-28-22-14-41.png"
  ),
  "7.15": (
    caption: [Female primates often show a preference for males with red fur or facial skin, as seen in this red uakari. This preference may have originated as a sensory bias related to foraging for red fruits and leaves.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-28-22-14-55.png"
  ),
  "7.16": (
    caption: [Phylogenetic analysis of primates supports the sensory bias hypothesis for red coloration preference. (A) Trichromatic color vision, which allows detection of red, evolved early in primate history. (B) Red skin/fur coloration appeared later. This sequence suggests that the preference for red was in place before the trait evolved in males.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-28-22-15-21.png"
  ),
  "7.17": (
    caption: [The male Physalaemus pustulosus frog adds a low-frequency "chuck" to its call to attract females. The evolution of this call and the female preference for it provide a key test of the sensory bias hypothesis.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-28-22-15-51.png"
  ),
  "7.18": (
    caption: [Phylogenetic and experimental evidence suggest a sensory bias for "chucks" in Physalaemus frogs. (A) The call consists of a "whine" and a "chuck." (B) The phylogenetic tree shows that the female preference for the chuck call evolved before the call itself, as females of the related species P. coloradorum (which lacks the chuck) still prefer calls with an artificially added chuck.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-28-22-16-08.png"
  ),
  "7.19": (
    caption: [Pavlovian conditioning can enhance male reproductive fitness. Male quail that learned to associate an experimental chamber with a mating opportunity produced significantly more spermatozoa than control males who did not learn the association.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-28-22-16-28.png"
  ),
  "7.20": (
    caption: [Adult learning can override juvenile sexual imprinting in Japanese quail. Although males were imprinted on brown females, they learned to associate blond females with mating opportunities. Consequently, they spent significantly more time near blond females, demonstrating that conditioning in adulthood shaped their preference.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-28-22-16-58.png"
  ),
  "7.21": (
    caption: [Male black grouse display on leks to attract females. They strut, flap their wings, and hiss. Females often observe these displays in groups, and their choices can be influenced by the choices of other females (mate-choice copying).],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-28-22-17-10.png"
  ),
  "7.22": (
    caption: [Female mate-choice copying is evident in sage grouse. As the number of females mating on a given day increases, the unanimity of their choice of male also increases at a rate faster than expected by chance, suggesting they are copying one another's decisions.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-28-22-17-26.png"
  ),
  "7.23": (
    caption: [A cross-fostering experiment was used to study cultural transmission in cowbirds. Juvenile birds from South Dakota (SD) were raised either by adults from their own population (regime 1) or by adults from an Indiana (IN) population (regime 2) to see how social environment affects song and mate preference.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-28-22-17-51.png"
  ),
  "7.24": (
    caption: [Male red deer assess rivals through a sequence of behaviors. An approach can lead to a roaring contest, which may be followed by a parallel walk to gauge size and strength. Fights typically only occur between closely matched individuals, with one stag usually withdrawing at an earlier stage.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-28-22-18-29.png"
  ),
  "7.25": (
    caption: [Roaring rate in red deer is an honest indicator of male condition and harem-holding status. Males in possession of a harem ("holders") roar significantly more often than solitary males or males outside the main mating (rut) season.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-28-22-18-52.png"
  ),
  "7.26": (
    caption: [Male elephant seals, which are much larger than females, engage in intense physical fights for control over harems of females during the breeding season. This intense competition drives extreme sexual dimorphism.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-28-22-19-01.png"
  ),
  "7.27": (
    caption: [In pinnipeds, there is a strong positive correlation between harem size and sexual size dimorphism. As the average harem size increases, the relative size of males compared to females also increases, a pattern driven by intense male-male competition.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-28-22-19-25.png"
  ),
  "7.28": (
    caption: [A parental male bluegill sunfish builds a nest and provides care for his eggs. He defends the nest from predators and fans the eggs to ensure they are well-oxygenated.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-28-22-19-41.png"
  ),
  "7.29": (
    caption: [Bluegill sunfish exhibit three different male reproductive morphs. (A) A parental male prepares a nest. (B) Smaller "sneaker" males hide and wait for an opportunity to rush in and fertilize eggs. (C-D) A "satellite" male, which mimics a female, positions himself to intercept a spawning. (E) A composite showing all three strategies.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-28-22-20-10.png"
  ),
  "table.7.1": (
    caption: [Female elephant seals protest mounts from subordinate males to incite male-male competition and increase their chances of mating with the dominant (alpha) male. Protests were far more frequent against non-dominant adults and subadults than against the alpha male.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-28-22-20-36.png"
  )
)
